Code playbacks allow instructors to create guided code walkthroughs showing how their code evolves from start to finish. Playback authors create narratives explaining their thought processes and students get to see reasoning behind each decision. The narrative can include visual feedback including whiteboard-style pictures, screenshots of output, and videos describing what the code is doing. This demonstration will show major enhancements to the Storyteller tool, used to create and display code playbacks, that transforms code playbacks from a relatively passive resources into ones where active learning takes place. The new AI assistant features let students ask questions about any code in the playback, generate practice problems tailored to their skill level, and get project ideas for extending examples. The AI understands the current code context and provides responses appropriate for the viewer's experience level. In addition, authors of code playbacks can use the AI assistant when building them. The AI assistant can suggest explanations and generate practice question/answers based on the code. The demonstration covers how instructors create AI-enhanced playbacks, how students use the new features, and evidence of improved engagement with the AI features. Attendees will learn to create their own interactive code playbacks that replace traditional textbooks with dynamic, conversational learning materials.